Any testing?
I did run redfish service validator.  Will document.
Can you add that? People do watch these. ;)

yes, I will before merge.  Still fighting with style issues on the generated files.

Who came up with the tested rule anyway? 😊

Mostly for others watching, 
I initially felt we didn't need the tested statement 
https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/docs/+/8506

But I think it has helped us a ton in bmcweb. 
We still get breaks, but I think without forcing developers to write down how they tested, many new developers would break things like the Redfish validator. bmcweb has had 176 contributors, which is a lot of people coming in.

> Mostly for others watching, 

To be clear for those watching, I was being sarcastic.  I fully support having tested statements.

> I initially felt we didn't need the tested statement 
> https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/docs/+/8506
> 
> But I think it has helped us a ton in bmcweb. 
> We still get breaks, but I think without forcing developers to write down how they tested, many new developers would break things like the Redfish validator. bmcweb has had 176 contributors, which is a lot of people coming in.


FWIW, the largest value in the tested statement isn't in that we don't break master, it's that future developers can run the same tests that were run initially to prove out a feature.  Many..... many times refactoring code I will use the tested statements for POST requests to test that a given flow works, without necessarily needing to craft a new test command myself.  Much of the time, the original developer of the feature is long gone.
100% on board with the concept, seems reasonable
don't see these used.
nlohmann is used, url_view is not, you're right.
Can we defer this for now?  Conditionally including headers is kinda messy.  I clean it up a bit in the next patch, but this one is harder.
Sure.
don't see these used either
Yeah, these are kind of a mess in the script.  I clean it up a little later in the series but it needs more work.
Acknowledged
